<taxonomicName id="2A720F034E9B1CB5ED6C9A930FAE168D" LSID="9A4F437C-3374-5FDD-8609-687311C56C14" authority="Linnaeus, 1758" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" genus="Salmo" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Mammalia Linnaeus, 1758</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="511180F3D6B09A5F108B2E64291FC70C" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" type="notes">
<paragraph id="A41C1A5E0BA09DCF41254CBA516C1BC6" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ABEF43421F767DF8BDAC35AD58994DA0" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
[
<emphasis id="B24B86677722526947674255991D1138" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">2 orders: 7 families: 12 genera: 13 species</emphasis>
]
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C5844EC036FECD9051DC653AEDBD934C" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
The name ' 
<taxonomicName id="3C251C61651DA30FB04C3791A858BD6A" class="Mammalia" genus="Salmo" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Mammalia</taxonomicName>
' was coined in 1758 by Linnaeus, from Late Latin (neuter plural) 'mammalis', meaning &quot;of the breast.&quot;
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D30764A3C796CFDC8A21BBE859D032CC" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
<taxonomicName id="11C3F57597F743E64E4A794BC5DFD733" class="Mammalia" genus="Salmo" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Mammalia</taxonomicName>
are a class of vertebrates containing 6,400 species worldwide (
<bibRefCitation id="9BB76546D9DBD4B8ED99E539113D71D4" author="Burgin, C. J." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Mammalogy" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" pagination="1 - 14" refId="B6747979" refString="Burgin, C. J., Colella, J. P., Kahn, P. L., Upham, N. S., 2018. How many species of mammals are there? Journal of Mammalogy 99 (1): 1 - 14" title="How many species of mammals are there?" volume="99" year="2018">Burgin et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Within British Columbia, 31 marine mammal species are represented among two orders, including 
<taxonomicName id="967C5694382F5CCE4ADFB0C0FC17CAC6" class="Mammalia" genus="Salmo" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Carnivora" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Carnivora</taxonomicName>
(carnivores) and 
<taxonomicName id="FCE7C185E5BEC64B20D4D8B6E3E74E40" class="Mammalia" genus="Salmo" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Cetacea</taxonomicName>
(cetaceans) (
<bibRefCitation id="95BB060F2329C466DC0EEE465913400E" author="Ford, J. K." journalOrPublisher="Royal British Columbia Museum, Victoria (BC, Canada)" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747988" refString="Ford, J. K., 2014. Marine mammals of British Columbia. Royal British Columbia Museum, Victoria (BC, Canada)" title="Marine mammals of British Columbia" year="2014">Ford 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Twenty-two marine mammals have been documented within the Salish Sea, including fifteen cetaceans, five species of pinniped and two mustelids (
<bibRefCitation id="E8B839DBCAEA1DDDF48983FA5346BDE7" author="Ford, J. K." journalOrPublisher="Royal British Columbia Museum, Victoria (BC, Canada)" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747988" refString="Ford, J. K., 2014. Marine mammals of British Columbia. Royal British Columbia Museum, Victoria (BC, Canada)" title="Marine mammals of British Columbia" year="2014">Ford 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Of these taxa, only 12 are known to commonly occur in the region. Thirteen species of marine mammal have been reported in waters around Galiano Island to date.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E88A4D8A0D66E3BE89FE0A1CE9408AB8" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
Among locally occurring cetaceans are: baleen whales, distinguished by their enlarged head containing baleen plates suspended from the upper jaw, their double blowhole and their thick blubber; and toothed whales, distinguished by their teeth and single external blowhole. Certain cetaceans, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4014F4F9C51B7CFF8DA60A3564409CC9" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" family="Balaenopteridae" genus="Balaenoptera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Balaenoptera physalus" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="physalus">
<emphasis id="3124825F925A73A37DE55035CEF718D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Balaenoptera physalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus, 1758) (fin whale) and 
<taxonomicName id="2342F3267A33D5DA0DFB1491C257A52E" authorityName="Lacepede" authorityYear="1804" class="Mammalia" family="Balaenopteridae" genus="Balaenoptera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Balaenoptera acutorostrata" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="acutorostrata">
<emphasis id="501EEEDE2A60DCAE2D1CC39C65376210" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Balaenoptera acutorostrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="249F7EB0504C252690054C296FF0E779" originalValue="Lacépède">Lacepede</normalizedToken>
, 1804 (common minke whale) have been recorded infrequently in local waters, whereas others, such as 
<taxonomicName id="90942D3E2074E5D3F78672B2D520BF52" baseAuthorityName="Borowski" baseAuthorityYear="1781" class="Mammalia" family="Balaenopteridae" genus="Megaptera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megaptera novaeangliae" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="novaeangliae">
<emphasis id="3A1FE73C3E53CC1E0C0AD8F2F6465035" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Megaptera novaeangliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Borowski, 1781 (humpback whale) and 
<taxonomicName id="1F17549B1EE8BB0E0BAA6340BC522BFE" class="Mammalia" family="Phocoenidae" genus="Phocoena" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phocoena phocoeana" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="phocoeana">
<emphasis id="B66B61BE3CB840F0CE4D991C71541B4B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Phocoena phocoeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus, 1758) (harbour porpoise), are commonly seen. Among carnivores, both aquatic pinnipeds, such as 
<taxonomicName id="8AC0602D91E04BAF9A84AB39CB6A1081" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1864" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Phoca" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phoca vitulina subsp. richardii" order="Carnivora" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="vitulina" subSpecies="richardii">
<emphasis id="55AA64A9A7D484D73513653D55E902D7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Phoca vitulina richardii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Gray, 1864 (harbour seal) and semi-aquatic fissipeds, such as 
<taxonomicName id="675A3825563E8E45E0A4406D213E8E60" baseAuthorityName="Schreber" baseAuthorityYear="1777" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Lontra" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lontra canadensis" order="Carnivora" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis id="7098665F1C2EA78697B1EBF1F485D17F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Lontra canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Schreber, 1777) (river otter), are represented. Presently, there are no known haulouts of 
<taxonomicName id="DA7C4F8AD51DE2A7DFC17DC356AB0A3B" baseAuthorityName="Gill" baseAuthorityYear="1866" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Mirounga" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mirounga angustirostris" order="Carnivora" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="angustirostris">
<emphasis id="67E20FF4DD5BEAC4DC1A2214A83A3EC6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Mirounga angustirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gill, 1866) (northern elephant seal) around Galiano Island, though they are known not far away on Salt Spring Island.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F84723EB0CE471AE14BDCDA9AA76101F" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
Populations of 
<taxonomicName id="D3C4C85FBC2B49D1038DBC7357401DFE" baseAuthorityName="Lilljeborg" baseAuthorityYear="1861" class="Mammalia" family="Eschrichtiidae" genus="Eschrichtius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eschrichtius robustus" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="2785000CC3A84164AA7D8217595126EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Eschrichtius robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lilljeborg, 1861) (grey whale), 
<taxonomicName id="31FEC1773D37BBF43FAA0FE5F9D5D654" genus="M." lsidName="M. novaeangliae" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" rank="species" species="novaeangliae">
<emphasis id="2766C472E8646942453A118816466CD7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">M. novaeangliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="F35D5DC7912B1E0787F8A6895466BCA5" class="Scaphopoda" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. phocoena" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="phocoena">
<emphasis id="C86002E34553EA0E85409E7E8FA82454" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">P. phocoena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the southern resident population of 
<taxonomicName id="092D4FA6C6F2F11960E74A203AED600F" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" family="Delphinidae" genus="Orcinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orcinus orca" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="orca">
<emphasis id="56681E08EF717F9735C40AE971B72DCC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Orcinus orca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus, 1758) (
<taxonomicName id="4096BF2F2B2ACD9889F332833CEB4ACA" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" family="Delphinidae" genus="Orcinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orcinus orca" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="orca">Orcinus orca</taxonomicName>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7DBF9815552AF1749572C7D29F4B7473" captionStart="Figure 21" captionStartId="F6748180" captionText="Figure 21. Mother (J 41) with baby (J 51) of the Southern Resident Killer Whale J Pod - Photograph by Karoline Cullen." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e76050.figure21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/630809" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">21</figureCitation>
) are currently ranked as species of conservation concern in the region (
<bibRefCitation id="DB8BD96F4DD6FCAE5BFDBE1685155806" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries and Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748004" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2009. Management plan for the Pacific harbour porpoise (Phocoena phocoena) in Canada. Species at Risk Act management plan series. Fisheries and Oceans Canada" title="Management plan for the Pacific harbour porpoise (Phocoena phocoena) in Canada. Species at Risk Act management plan series" year="2009">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2009a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="23FFD832300E2111863CEE87F94C2131" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries and Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748020" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2010. Management plan for the Eastern Pacific grey whale (Eschrichtius robustus) in Canada. Species at Risk Act management plan series. Fisheries and Oceans Canada" title="Management plan for the Eastern Pacific grey whale (Eschrichtius robustus) in Canada. Species at Risk Act management plan series" year="2010">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2010</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="3101B4AB65D1AE59079F1FF1FA9350DE" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries and Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748028" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2013. Recovery strategy for the North Pacific humpback whale (Megaptera novaeangliae) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series. Fisheries and Oceans Canada" title="Recovery strategy for the North Pacific humpback whale (Megaptera novaeangliae) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series" year="2013">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2013</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="10C48FB0B7E711BCF0727D5DB4E39C00" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries &amp; Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748036" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2018. Recovery strategy for the northern and southern resident killer whales (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series. Fisheries &amp; Oceans Canada" title="Recovery strategy for the northern and southern resident killer whales (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series" year="2018">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2018a</bibRefCitation>
). Northern resident, transient and offshore orcas are also known to traverse local waters and are listed as threatened within Canada (
<bibRefCitation id="A0DDE5C4E433B84AB91CBFB7C571F87F" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries and Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747996" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2007. Recovery strategy for the transient killer whale (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series. Fisheries and Oceans Canada" title="Recovery strategy for the transient killer whale (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series" year="2007">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2007</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="064F977C06D8CF427B3827B484ADF3A9" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries and Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748012" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2009. Management plan for the offshore killer whale (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act management plan series. Fisheries and Oceans Canada" title="Management plan for the offshore killer whale (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act management plan series" year="2009">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2009b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="26218A9B1AFD41948CD0475CEC9E3280" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries &amp; Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748036" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2018. Recovery strategy for the northern and southern resident killer whales (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series. Fisheries &amp; Oceans Canada" title="Recovery strategy for the northern and southern resident killer whales (Orcinus orca) in Canada. Species at Risk Act recovery strategy series" year="2018">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2018a</bibRefCitation>
). Regional accounts of marine mammals include 
<bibRefCitation id="4D801966F5124606714249126340F47C" author="Williams, R." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Cetacean Research and Management" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" pagination="15 - 28" refId="B6748044" refString="Williams, R., Thomas, L., 2007. Distribution and abundance of marine mammals in the coastal waters of British Columbia, Canada. Journal of Cetacean Research and Management 9: 15 - 28" title="Distribution and abundance of marine mammals in the coastal waters of British Columbia, Canada" volume="9" year="2007">Williams and Thomas (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="6B82D8369DDE0DA23AA1980F49C83189" author="Ford, J. K." journalOrPublisher="Royal British Columbia Museum, Victoria (BC, Canada)" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747988" refString="Ford, J. K., 2014. Marine mammals of British Columbia. Royal British Columbia Museum, Victoria (BC, Canada)" title="Marine mammals of British Columbia" year="2014">Ford (2014)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="99FC9353E2D2A66B45938C96B2CD745B" author="Moore, R. D." journalOrPublisher="Ministry of Forests and Range, Victoria" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748053" refString="Nagorsen D. Mammals of British Columbia (2014) https://ibis.geog.ubc.ca/biodiversity/efauna/documents/MammalsofBCChecklist.pdf 2021-02-13T00:00:00+02:00" year="2010">Nagorsen (2014)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="3620C9814550F281B0FA04630ACFE267" author="Harvey, G. K." journalOrPublisher="Ecosphere" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" pagination=": e 01884" refId="B6748073" refString="Harvey, G. K., Nelson, T. A., Fox, C. H., Paquet, P. C., 2017. Quantifying marine mammal hotspots in British Columbia, Canada. Ecosphere 8 (7): e01884" title="Quantifying marine mammal hotspots in British Columbia, Canada" volume="8" year="2017">Harvey et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
. For annotated records of mammals reported for Galiano Island, see supplementary materials (Suppl. material 20).
</paragraph>
